const module1Data = GovModuleContent(
  id: 1,
  title: 'Financial Management Primer',
  gameTitle: 'Three Pillars Term Match',
  gameDescription: 'Match each English financial term with its Arabic translation.',
  gameType: GameType.memoryMatch,
  slides: [
    {'title': '1.1 Accounting vs. Finance: Understanding the Difference', 'content': 'Before we dive into the three pillars, we need to clear up one of the most common confusions in the business world: the difference between Accounting and Finance.\n\nAccounting looks backward. It is the discipline of recording, classifying, and summarizing financial transactions that have already happened. Accountants produce financial statements — structured reports that show stakeholders exactly what occurred.\n\nFinance looks forward. It takes the information that accounting produces and uses it to make decisions about the future. Finance professionals ask: Should we take on more debt? Is this acquisition worth pursuing?\n\nThink of it this way: if a company were a car, Accounting would be the dashboard — it tells you your speed, fuel level, and engine temperature. Finance would be the driver — it uses that information to decide when to accelerate, brake, and which route to take.', 'keyPoint': 'Accounting = Recording & Reporting (backward-looking) • Finance = Analysis & Decision-making (forward-looking) • Accounting follows standards (IFRS, GAAP); Finance uses judgment • The CFO bridges both functions'},
    {'title': '1.2 How Accounting and Finance Work Together', 'content': 'Accounting produces three core financial statements that finance professionals rely on daily:\n\n1. The Income Statement — shows revenue, expenses, and profit or loss over a period. Think of it as the "report card" for the year.\n\n2. The Balance Sheet — shows what the organization owns (assets), what it owes (liabilities), and the residual belonging to owners (equity) at a specific point in time. Think of it as a "photograph" of financial health.\n\n3. The Cash Flow Statement — tracks the actual movement of cash in and out of the organization, organized by operating, investing, and financing activities.\n\nAccounting records that revenue grew 15% this quarter. Finance asks: Why? Was it sustainable? Should we invest more in that product line?', 'keyPoint': 'The three financial statements — Income Statement, Balance Sheet, and Cash Flow Statement — are the common language between accounting and finance.'},
    {'title': '1.3 The Three Core Financial Decisions', 'content': 'Every financial decision an organization makes falls into one of three buckets:\n\nFinancing Decisions — "Where does the money come from?" Financing decisions determine how the organization raises money. Should it borrow from banks? Issue bonds? Sell shares?\n\nInvesting Decisions — "Where does the money go?" Once you have capital, you must decide where to deploy it. Should you build a new factory? Acquire a competitor?\n\nOperating Decisions — "How do we manage day-to-day?" Even with great financing and smart investments, an organization can fail if it doesn\'t manage its daily financial operations well.\n\nThese three categories are deeply interconnected. Financing provides the fuel, investing determines the direction, and operating keeps the engine running.', 'keyPoint': 'Financing = Where does the money come from? • Investing = Where does the money go? • Operating = How do we manage day-to-day? • All three are interconnected'},
    {'title': '1.4 Spotting Financial Decisions in Real-World Headlines', 'content': 'One of the best ways to internalize the Three Pillars framework is to practice spotting financial decisions in real-world business news.\n\nFinancing headlines: "raises capital," "issues bonds," "IPO," "sukuk issuance," or "dividend payout."\n\nInvesting headlines: "acquires," "merges with," "builds new plant," "launches R&D center," "capital expenditure."\n\nOperating headlines: "cuts costs," "improves efficiency," "supply chain optimization," "cash flow issues."\n\nSome headlines combine pillars. "Company borrows \$1B to fund acquisition" is both a financing decision (issuing debt) and an investing decision (buying another company).', 'keyPoint': 'Exercise: For the next week, read one business headline per day and classify it as Financing, Investing, or Operating.'},
    {'title': '1.5 Pillar 1: Financing — Where Does the Money Come From?', 'content': 'The first pillar of finance addresses the most fundamental question: Where does the money come from?\n\nEvery organization needs capital. Financing decisions determine how that capital is raised. There are two fundamental sources:\n\nDebt — borrowing money from lenders (banks, bondholders, or other creditors). You must repay the principal plus interest. Lenders do not own any part of your company.\n\nEquity — raising money from owners or investors who receive an ownership stake. Equity investors share in the profits and bear the risk of loss. They have no guaranteed return.\n\nThe financing decision is not simply "debt or equity" — it is about finding the right mix. Too much debt increases the risk of financial distress. Too much equity dilutes ownership and is expensive.', 'keyPoint': 'Two sources of capital: Debt and Equity • Debt = borrowing (must repay + interest, no ownership given up) • Equity = ownership (share profits, no mandatory repayment) • The key decision is finding the right mix'},
    {'title': '1.6 Debt Instruments: Short-Term and Long-Term Loans', 'content': 'Loans are the most straightforward form of debt financing.\n\nShort-Term Loans (< 1 year) are used for immediate, temporary needs:\n• Revolving Credit Facilities — a pre-approved borrowing limit, like a corporate credit card\n• Overdraft Facilities — withdrawing more than your account balance\n• Commercial Paper — short-term unsecured promissory notes\n\nLong-Term Loans (> 1 year) are used for major investments:\n• Term Loans — a lump sum repaid in regular installments over 3–10+ years\n• Syndicated Loans — a group of banks shares a large loan\n\nBanks assess creditworthiness, require collateral, and impose covenants — conditions the borrower must comply with.', 'keyPoint': 'Short-term loans (<1 year): revolving credit, overdraft, commercial paper • Long-term loans (>1 year): term loans, syndicated loans • Banks assess creditworthiness, require collateral, and impose covenants'},
    {'title': '1.7 Debt Instruments: Bonds and Sukuk', 'content': 'While loans involve borrowing from a bank, bonds and sukuk allow organizations to borrow from the capital markets — raising money directly from many investors at once.\n\nA Bond is a debt security. The issuer sells bonds to investors, promising periodic interest (the coupon) and return of principal at maturity. Credit rating agencies rate bonds from AAA (safest) to D (default).\n\nA Sukuk is the Islamic finance equivalent. Because Sharia law prohibits interest (riba), sukuk holders receive ownership in an underlying tangible asset or project. Returns come from the asset\'s profits or rental income — not from interest.\n\nSaudi Arabia is one of the world\'s largest sukuk markets, with both the government and major corporations regularly issuing sukuk.', 'keyPoint': 'Bonds: debt securities with coupon (interest) payments and maturity • Sukuk: Sharia-compliant — investors own a share of an underlying asset • Bond = "I owe you money + interest" | Sukuk = "You own a piece of this asset"'},
    {'title': '1.8 Equity Instruments: Shares and Retained Earnings', 'content': 'The second source of capital is equity — raising money by selling ownership stakes or retaining profits.\n\n• IPO (Initial Public Offering): selling shares to the public for the first time. Saudi Aramco\'s 2019 IPO raised \$25.6 billion — the largest in history.\n\n• Secondary Offerings: issuing additional shares to raise more capital, which dilutes existing shareholders.\n\n• Rights Issues: existing shareholders get first right to buy new shares at a discount.\n\n• Retained Earnings: profits kept in the business — the most common and cheapest equity source. No need to issue shares or pay investment banks.\n\nThe key trade-off: shareholders expect higher returns than lenders because they bear more risk. This makes equity more expensive than debt, but it doesn\'t require mandatory payments.', 'keyPoint': 'IPO: selling shares publicly for the first time • Retained earnings: cheapest equity source • Equity is more expensive than debt but more flexible (no mandatory payments)'},
    {'title': '1.9 Debt vs. Equity: Comparing the Trade-offs', 'content': 'Debt Advantages: (1) Cheaper — interest is often tax-deductible. (2) No ownership dilution. (3) Predictable fixed payments.\n\nDebt Disadvantages: (1) Mandatory payments — miss one and you risk default. (2) Covenants restrict what you can do. (3) Too much debt = bankruptcy risk.\n\nEquity Advantages: (1) No mandatory payments — dividends are optional. (2) No maturity date. (3) Lower financial risk.\n\nEquity Disadvantages: (1) More expensive — shareholders demand higher returns. (2) Ownership dilution. (3) Profit sharing with investors.\n\nThe bottom line: Debt is cheaper but riskier (mandatory payments). Equity is more expensive but safer (flexible payments). Every company uses some combination of both.', 'keyPoint': 'Debt: cheaper, no dilution, but mandatory payments and bankruptcy risk • Equity: flexible, no default risk, but expensive and dilutes ownership • Too much debt = risk of bankruptcy. Too much equity = expensive. The art is finding the balance.'},
    {'title': '1.10 Capital Structure: Finding the Right Mix', 'content': 'Capital Structure is the specific proportion of debt and equity that a company uses to finance its operations.\n\nA company with 70% debt and 30% equity has a very different risk profile than one with 30% debt and 70% equity. The first is "highly leveraged" — pays less for capital but faces significant risk if revenues decline.\n\nDifferent industries have different capital structures:\n• Utilities: ~60-70% debt (stable, predictable cash flows)\n• Real Estate: ~50-65% debt (physical assets as collateral)\n• Technology: ~10-30% debt (volatile revenues)\n• Pharmaceuticals: ~15-35% debt (long R&D cycles)\n\nThere is no single "correct" capital structure. The optimal mix depends on the company\'s industry, growth stage, revenue stability, and management\'s risk tolerance.', 'keyPoint': 'Capital Structure = proportion of debt vs. equity • High debt = cheaper but riskier • High equity = safer but more expensive • Optimal structure varies by industry and risk tolerance'},
    {'title': '1.11 WACC: Measuring the Cost of Capital', 'content': 'The Weighted Average Cost of Capital (WACC) is the single number that captures how much it costs a company to fund itself.\n\nExample: A company that is 40% debt and 60% equity. After-tax cost of debt is 4%, cost of equity is 11%.\nWACC = (40% × 4%) + (60% × 11%) = 1.6% + 6.6% = 8.2%\n\nThis means the company must earn at least 8.2% return on everything it invests just to break even.\n\nWhy WACC matters: Any project earning above WACC creates value. Any project earning below WACC destroys value.\n\nDebt cost is calculated after tax because interest is tax-deductible. If pre-tax cost is 5% and tax rate is 20%, after-tax cost = 5% × (1 - 0.20) = 4%.', 'keyPoint': 'WACC = (E/V × Cost of Equity) + (D/V × Cost of Debt × (1 − Tax Rate)) • Projects above WACC create value; below WACC destroy value • Optimizing capital structure minimizes WACC'},
    {'title': '1.12 Pillar 2: Investing — Where Does the Money Go?', 'content': 'The second pillar addresses the next logical question: now that we have raised capital, where should we put it?\n\nInvesting decisions determine how an organization deploys its capital to generate future returns. Every dollar invested today should produce more than a dollar of value in the future.\n\nInvestment decisions fall into two broad categories:\n\nInternal Investment — deploying capital within your own organization to strengthen and grow the core business. This is "organic growth."\n\nExternal Investment — deploying capital outside your organization, either by acquiring other companies (M&A) or by purchasing financial assets.\n\nThe critical question: Does the expected return exceed our cost of capital (WACC)? If yes, the investment creates value. If no, it destroys value.', 'keyPoint': 'Investing = deploying capital for future returns • Internal: grow your own business (organic growth) • External: acquire other companies or buy financial assets • Golden rule: Deploy capital only where expected return exceeds WACC'},
    {'title': '1.13 Internal Investment: Growing the Core Business', 'content': 'Internal investment means putting capital back into your own organization. Capital Expenditure (CapEx) includes:\n\n• New Facilities — building factories, warehouses, offices\n• Machinery & Equipment — purchasing or upgrading production equipment\n• Technology & IT Systems — enterprise software, cybersecurity, cloud infrastructure\n• Research & Development (R&D) — developing new products and processes. Pharma companies spend 15-20% of revenue on R&D.\n• Human Capital — training employees, leadership development, hiring talent\n\nInternal investment is slower than M&A, but you maintain full control and avoid integration risks. Amazon, Toyota, and Saudi Aramco built their dominance primarily through relentless internal investment.', 'keyPoint': 'CapEx categories: facilities, machinery, technology, R&D, human capital • Internal investment = slower but full control and no integration risk'},
    {'title': '1.14 External Investment: Mergers & Acquisitions', 'content': 'The most significant form of external investment is Mergers & Acquisitions (M&A).\n\nA Merger: two companies agree to combine into a single new entity.\nAn Acquisition: one company purchases another.\n\nWhy do companies pursue M&A?\n• Market Share — buy a competitor to double your position overnight\n• Technology & Talent — acquire valuable tech or skilled employees faster than building internally\n• Synergies — combined entity is more efficient (cost synergies from eliminating duplicates; revenue synergies from cross-selling)\n• Geographic Expansion — instant access to a new market\n\nHowever, M&A is risky. Over 50% of acquisitions fail to deliver expected value. Common pitfalls: overpaying, cultural clashes, and underestimating integration difficulty.', 'keyPoint': 'Merger = two companies combine into new entity • Acquisition = one company purchases another • Over 50% of M&A deals fail — due diligence is essential'},
    {'title': '1.15 Three Types of Mergers & Acquisitions', 'content': 'Not all M&A deals are the same:\n\nHorizontal Merger — combining with a company in the same industry, at the same stage of the value chain. You\'re merging with a direct competitor.\nExample: Two airlines merging to become the dominant carrier.\n\nVertical Merger — combining with a company in the same supply chain but at a different stage.\nExample: An oil company acquiring a chain of gas stations (downstream integration).\n\nConglomerate Merger — combining with a company in a completely unrelated industry. Purpose: diversify to reduce risk.\nExample: Samsung operates in electronics, construction, shipbuilding, and life insurance.\n\nEach type carries different risks: horizontal mergers face antitrust scrutiny; vertical mergers require managing different business models; conglomerates face the challenge of managing unrelated businesses.', 'keyPoint': 'Horizontal: same industry, same level → market share and scale • Vertical: same supply chain, different level → control and cost reduction • Conglomerate: unrelated industries → risk diversification'},
    {'title': '1.16 Financial Investment as an Alternative', 'content': 'Not every external investment requires buying an entire company. Financial Investment — purchasing minority stakes in stocks, bonds, or funds — is a lighter-weight alternative.\n\nThe investor does not seek operational control. The goal is purely financial: generate income (dividends, interest) and/or capital gains (price appreciation).\n\nFinancial investment is attractive because it is highly liquid, requires less capital, involves no integration headaches, and allows easy diversification.\n\nSovereign Wealth Funds like Saudi Arabia\'s PIF hold positions across technology, entertainment, sports, and infrastructure — without necessarily acquiring full ownership.\n\nA "strategic stake" of 10-30% gives influence (a board seat) without full acquisition — a common approach for exploring a market before committing.', 'keyPoint': 'Financial investment = buying securities for returns, not control • More liquid, cheaper, and lower-risk than M&A • Strategic stakes (10-30%) offer influence without full acquisition'},
    {'title': '1.17 Evaluating Investments: Net Present Value (NPV)', 'content': 'NPV is built on a simple insight: a dollar today is worth more than a dollar tomorrow (Time Value of Money).\n\nNPV discounts all expected future cash flows back to today using a discount rate (typically WACC), then subtracts the initial investment cost.\n\nExample: A project costs \$1,000,000 upfront and generates \$350,000/year for 4 years. WACC is 10%.\nYear 1: \$350,000 ÷ 1.10 = \$318,182\nYear 2: \$350,000 ÷ 1.21 = \$289,256\nYear 3: \$350,000 ÷ 1.331 = \$263,006\nYear 4: \$350,000 ÷ 1.4641 = \$239,096\nTotal PV = \$1,109,540\nNPV = \$1,109,540 − \$1,000,000 = +\$109,540 → Accept!\n\nDecision rule: NPV > 0 → Accept (creates value). NPV < 0 → Reject (destroys value).', 'keyPoint': 'NPV = Σ [Cash Flow_t ÷ (1 + r)^t] − Initial Investment • NPV > 0 → Accept • NPV < 0 → Reject • When comparing projects, pick the highest NPV'},
    {'title': '1.18 Evaluating Investments: Internal Rate of Return (IRR)', 'content': 'IRR is the discount rate that makes the NPV of an investment exactly equal to zero — the break-even rate of return.\n\nUsing the same example: at 10% WACC, NPV was +\$109,540. If we increase the discount rate, NPV decreases. The IRR is where NPV hits exactly zero — approximately 15%.\n\nDecision rule: IRR > WACC → Accept. IRR < WACC → Reject.\nWith 10% WACC and 15% IRR, the project earns 5 percentage points above the cost of capital.\n\nIRR is intuitive — "this project returns 15%" is easy to communicate. However, for mutually exclusive projects, a smaller project might have higher IRR but lower NPV. In these cases, trust NPV.\n\nBest practice: use both NPV and IRR together. NPV gives "how much value"; IRR gives "what % return."', 'keyPoint': 'IRR = the rate where NPV equals zero • IRR > WACC → Accept; IRR < WACC → Reject • For mutually exclusive projects, trust NPV over IRR • Best practice: use both NPV and IRR together'},
    {'title': '1.19 Pillar 3: Operating — Managing Day-to-Day Finance', 'content': 'The third pillar addresses the most immediate question: how do we manage day-to-day financial operations?\n\nYou can have brilliant financing and perfect investments, but if you cannot collect from customers, pay suppliers on time, and keep cash in the bank, the business will fail.\n\nOperating decisions break down into two components:\n\nWorking Capital Management (WCM) — managing "money on paper." The timing gap between when you sell something and when you get paid, and between when you receive goods and when you pay for them.\n\nCash Flow Management — managing "money on hand." Actual cash in your bank account. It doesn\'t matter what your accounting records say if your bank balance is zero.\n\nWCM uses the accounting lens (accrual basis). Cash flow management uses the cash lens (cash basis).', 'keyPoint': 'Operating decisions manage the day-to-day financial engine • Two components: WCM (money on paper) and Cash Flow (money on hand) • Great financing + smart investing + poor operations = business failure'},
    {'title': '1.20 Working Capital Management: Money on Paper', 'content': 'The three core components of working capital:\n\nAccounts Receivable (A/R) — money customers owe you for goods already delivered. Days Sales Outstanding (DSO) measures collection time.\n\nInventory — goods purchased/produced but not yet sold. Ties up cash. Days Inventory Outstanding (DIO) measures how long inventory sits.\n\nAccounts Payable (A/P) — money you owe suppliers. Days Payable Outstanding (DPO) measures how long you take to pay.\n\nWorking Capital = Current Assets − Current Liabilities ≈ A/R + Inventory − A/P\n\nThe Cash Conversion Cycle (CCC) ties it together:\nCCC = DSO + DIO − DPO\n\nExample: 45 days to collect + 30 days in inventory − 40 days to pay = 35 day cycle. Shorter is better — cash cycles faster.', 'keyPoint': 'A/R = what customers owe you (DSO) • Inventory = goods awaiting sale (DIO) • A/P = what you owe suppliers (DPO) • Cash Conversion Cycle = DSO + DIO − DPO (shorter is better)'},
    {'title': '1.21 Cash Flow Management: Money on Hand', 'content': '"Cash is king" — without cash, you cannot pay salaries, rent, suppliers, or taxes. A company can be profitable on its income statement and still go bankrupt if it runs out of cash.\n\nKey elements of cash flow management:\n\n• Cash Forecasting — projecting future cash inflows and outflows weekly, monthly, and quarterly. Anticipate shortfalls before they happen.\n\n• Cash Reserves — maintaining 1-3 months of operating expenses as a buffer for unexpected events.\n\n• Short-Term Investing — invest excess cash in treasury bills, money market funds, or CDs rather than letting it sit idle.\n\n• Cash Acceleration — speed up inflows: early-payment discounts, electronic invoicing, automated reminders, factoring.\n\nThe fundamental insight: profit and cash are not the same thing.', 'keyPoint': 'Cash flow management = ensuring sufficient actual cash at all times • Profit ≠ Cash — profitable companies can go bankrupt without cash • Core activities: forecasting, reserves, short-term investing, acceleration'},
    {'title': '1.22 Connecting Operating Decisions to Financial Statements', 'content': 'Working Capital Management links to the Income Statement — records transactions on an accrual basis (revenue when earned, expenses when incurred).\n\nCash Flow Management links to the Cash Flow Statement — records actual movement of cash.\n\nThe bridge: The Cash Flow Statement starts with Net Income and adjusts:\n• Add back non-cash expenses (depreciation reduces profit but no cash leaves)\n• Adjust for working capital changes (increased A/R = revenue earned but cash not collected)\n\nExample: \$100K revenue, \$70K expenses (incl. \$10K depreciation), \$25K uncollected receivables.\nIncome Statement: \$100K − \$70K = \$30K profit\nCash Flow: \$30K + \$10K depreciation − \$25K uncollected = \$15K actual cash\n\nProfit is \$30K, but you only have \$15K in cash.', 'keyPoint': 'Cash from Operations = Net Income + Depreciation ± Changes in Working Capital • WCM → Income Statement (accrual) • Cash Management → Cash Flow Statement (cash basis)'},
    {'title': '1.23 Summary: The Three Pillars of Finance Framework', 'content': 'Pillar 1 — Financing: "Where does the money come from?" Debt (loans, bonds, sukuk) and Equity (IPO, retained earnings). Capital Structure defines the mix. WACC measures its cost.\n\nPillar 2 — Investing: "Where does the money go?" Internal (CapEx, R&D, technology) or External (M&A, financial investments). NPV and IRR evaluate value creation. Golden rule: invest only where returns exceed WACC.\n\nPillar 3 — Operating: "How do we manage day-to-day?" Working Capital Management (money on paper, Cash Conversion Cycle, Income Statement) and Cash Flow Management (money on hand, Cash Flow Statement).\n\nThese three pillars map directly to the three sections of the Cash Flow Statement: Cash from Financing, Investing, and Operating Activities. This is not a coincidence.', 'keyPoint': 'Financing: Debt & Equity → Capital Structure → WACC • Investing: Internal & External → NPV & IRR • Operating: WCM + Cash Mgmt • The three pillars = the three sections of the Cash Flow Statement'},
    {'title': '1.24 Module Summary', 'content': 'This module covered the foundation for everything that follows.\n\nEvery organization in the world faces the same three fundamental financial questions:\n1. Where does the money come from? (Financing)\n2. Where does the money go? (Investing)\n3. How do we manage the day-to-day? (Operating)\n\nThese form the Three Pillars of Finance — the DNA of every financial decision, every financial statement, and every strategic plan.\n\nYou learned how Accounting and Finance differ, explored each pillar in depth — including specific instruments, tools, and frameworks — and saw how they connect to the financial statements.\n\nYou now have a complete mental framework for any financial situation you encounter.', 'keyPoint': 'Three Pillars: Financing (raise it) → Investing (deploy it) → Operating (manage it) • This framework is the foundation for all financial decision-making'},
  ],
